.EE
.TP
\f[B]\-utf8\f[R]
Output in UTF8 format (plain text only)
.TP
\f[B]\-in\f[R] / \f[B]\-mm\f[R] / \f[B]\-cm\f[R]
Output dimensions in inches, millimetres or centimetres instead of
points.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-page\-info[\-json]\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-in |
\-cm | \-mm]
.PP
List page information in plain (\f[B]\-page\-info\f[R]) or JSON
(\f[B]\-page\-info\-json\f[R]) format.
.IP
.EX
cpdf \-page\-info 14psfonts.pdf
Page 1:
Label: i
MediaBox: 0.000000 0.000000 600.000000 450.000000
CropBox: 200.000000 200.000000 500.000000 500.000000
BleedBox:
TrimBox:
ArtBox:
Rotation: 0
Annotations: 0
.EE
.TP
\f[B]\-in\f[R] / \f[B]\-mm\f[R] / \f[B]\-cm\f[R]
Output dimensions in inches, millimetres or centimetres instead of
points.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-pages in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Print the number of pages in the file.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-title <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [\-also\-set\-xmp]
[\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-author <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-also\-set\-xmp] [\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-subject <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-also\-set\-xmp] [\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-keywords <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-also\-set\-xmp] [\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-creator <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-also\-set\-xmp] [\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-producer <string>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-also\-set\-xmp] [\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set metadata.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-create <date>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [\-also\-set\-xmp]
[\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-modify <date>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [\-also\-set\-xmp]
[\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set creation or modification dates.
See Appendix A of cpdfmanual.pdf for details of the PDF date format.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-trapped in.pdf\f[R] [\-also\-set\-xmp]
[\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-untrapped in.pdf\f[R] [\-also\-set\-xmp]
[\-just\-set\-xmp] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the trapped status of a PDF.
.TP
\f[B]\-also\-set\-xmp\f[R]
Set the XMP metadata if the field is present, in addition to setting the
old\-style PDF metadata.
.TP
\f[B]\-just\-set\-xmp\f[R]
Just set the XMP metadata, if the field is present, in addition to the
old\-style PDF metadata.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-page\-layout <layout> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the page layout: one of \f[B]SinglePage\f[R], \f[B]OneColumn\f[R],
\f[B]TwoColumnLeft\f[R], \f[B]TwoColumnRight\f[R],
\f[B]TwoPageLeft\f[R], \f[B]TwoPageRight\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-page\-mode <mode> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the page mode: one of \f[B]UseNone\f[R], \f[B]UseOutlines\f[R],
\f[B]UseThumbs\f[R], \f[B]FullScreen\f[R], \f[B]UseOC\f[R],
\f[B]UseAttachments\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-non\-full\-screen\-page\-mode <mode> in.pdf \-o
out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the non full screen mode for a PDF with FullScreen page mode: one of
\f[B]UseNone\f[R], \f[B]UseOutlines\f[R], \f[B]UseThumbs\f[R],
\f[B]UseAttachments\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-hide\-toolbar <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Hide or reveal the viewer\(cqs toolbar.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-hide\-menubar <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Hide or reveal the viewer\(cqs menubar.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-hide\-window\-ui <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Hide or reveal the window\(cqs scroll bars.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-fit\-window <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Resize the document\(cqs windows to fit the size of the first page.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-center\-window <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Position the document window in the center of the screen.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-display\-doc\-title <true | false> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Display the document title instead of the file name in the title bar.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-open\-at\-page <n> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the document to open at the given page number.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-open\-at\-page\-fit <n> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the document to open at the given page number scaled to fit the
window.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-open\-at\-page\-custom <destination> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the document to open at a custom destination.
See cpdfmanual.pdf for details.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-language <language> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the document\(cqs global language, for example \(lqen\-US\(rq
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-metadata <filename> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Replace or add XMP metadata.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-remove\-metadata in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove the main XMP metadata stream.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-remove\-all\-metadata in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove all XMP metadata streams.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-print\-metadata in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Print the XMP metadata stream to standard output.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-extract\-all\-metadata in.pdf \-o <path>\f[R]
.PP
Extract XMP metadata streams to the given directory.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-create\-metadata in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Create or replace XMP metadata from old\-style metadata.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-set\-metadata\-date <date> in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Set the XMP metadata date.
See Appendix A in cpdfmanual.pdf for date format details.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-add\-page\-labels in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-label\-style
<style>] [\-label\-prefix <string>] [\-label\-startval <n>]
[\-labels\-progress] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Add page labels to a PDF.
Multiple calls may be used to add multiple ranges of page labels.
.TP
\f[B]\-label\-style\f[R]
One of \f[B]DecimalArabic\f[R], \f[B]LowercaseRoman\f[R],
\f[B]UppercaseRoman\f[R], \f[B]LowercaseLetters\f[R],
\f[B]UppercaseLetters\f[R], \f[B]NoLabelPrefixOnly\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-label\-prefix\f[R]
The textual prefix for these labels.
.TP
\f[B]\-label\-startval\f[R]
By default the labels begin at page number 1 for each range.
To override this, we can use \f[B]\-label\-startval\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-labels\-progress\f[R]
make sure the start value progresses between sub\-ranges when the page
range specified is disjoint, e.g \(lq1\-9, 30\-40\(rq or \(lqodd\(rq.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-remove\-page\-labels in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove the page labels.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-print\-page\-labels[\-json] in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Print the page labels in plain text (\f[B]\-print\-page\-labels\f[R]) or
JSON (\f[B]\-print\-page\-labels\-json\f[R]) format.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-composition[\-json] in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Print the composition of a PDF, showing how much space is taken by
images, fonts etc.
.IP
.EX
cpdf \-composition cpdfmanual.pdf
Images: 0 bytes (0.00%)
Fonts: 144731 bytes (46.72%)
Content streams: 132767 bytes (42.85%)
Structure Info: 0 bytes (0.00%)
Attached Files: 0 bytes (0.00%)
XRef Table: 21082 bytes (6.80%)
Piece Info: 0 bytes (0.00%)
Unclassified: 11229 bytes (3.62%)
.EE
.SH 12. FILE ATTACHMENTS
\f[B]cpdf \-attach\-file <filename>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [\-to\-page
<n>] [\-afd <string>] [\-afr <relationship>] [\-attach\-file \&...]
\f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Attach a file to a PDF, given its filename.
.TP
\f[B]\-to\-page\f[R] <n>
Instead of attaching globally, add it as an attachment on a single page.
.TP
\f[B]\-afd\f[R] <string>
Supply the textual description for this attachment.
.TP
\f[B]\-afr\f[R] <relationship>
Supply the so\-called Relationship for this attachment.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-list\-attached\-files\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [\-json]
[\-include\-data]
.PP
List attached files.
.TP
\f[B]\-json\f[R]
List attached files in JSON format.
See cpdfmanual.pdf for full details.
.TP
\f[B]\-include\-data\f[R]
Include the attachment file data when listing in JSON format.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-remove\-files in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove attached files from a PDF.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-dump\-attachments in.pdf \-o <path>\f[R]
.PP
Extract the attachments to a given directory.
.SH 13. IMAGES
\f[B]cpdf \-list\-images[\-json]\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>]
[\-inline]
.PP
List the images in a file together with their object number, page
numbers, image name, width, height, size in bytes, bits per pixel,
colour space, compression method, mask type and mask object number.
Either in plain text (\f[B]\-list\-images\f[R]) or JSON
(\f[B]\-list\-images\-json\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\-inline\f[R]
Also list inline images.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-list\-images\-used[\-json]\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>]
[\-inline]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-image\-resolution[\-json] <n>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[<range>] [\-inline]
.PP
The \f[B]\-list\-images\-used\f[R] and
\f[B]\-list\-images\-used\-json\f[R] operations list the images at point
of use with their page number, image name, width in pixels, height in
pixels, x resolution, y resolution and object number.
Using \f[B]\-image\-resolution\f[R] or
\f[B]\-image\-resolution\-json\f[R] instead reports only such images as
do not reach a minimum resolution.
.TP
\f[B]\-inline\f[R]
Also list inline images.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-extract\-images in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-im <path>] [\-p2p
<path>] [\-dedup | \-dedup\-perpage] [\-raw] [\-inline] [\-merge\-masks]
\f[B]\-o <path>\f[R]
.PP
Extract images to a given path e.g \(lqoutput/%%%\(rq, which would
create output/001.jpg, output/002.png and so on.
JPEG, JPEG2000 and lossless JBIG2 images are extracted directly.
Lossy JBIG2 images are extracted in sections.
Other images are written as PNGs, processed with ImageMagick.
.TP
\f[B]\-im\f[R] <path>
Provide path to ImageMagick.
.TP
\f[B]\-p2p\f[R] <path>
Provide path to pnmtopng if ImageMagick not available.
.TP
\f[B]\-dedup\f[R]
Deduplicate images, extracting only once even if multiply\-included.
.TP
\f[B]\-dedup\-per\-page\f[R]
Deduplicate images, but only per\-page.
.TP
\f[B]\-raw\f[R]
Output .pnm files instead of .png.
.TP
\f[B]\-inline\f[R]
Also extract inline images.
.TP
\f[B]\-merge\-masks\f[R]
Merge soft masks with their images when extracting.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-extract\-single\-image <object number>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-im <path>] [\-p2p <path>] [\-raw] [\-merge\-masks] \f[B]\-o
<filename>\f[R]
.PP
Extract a single image, given its object number.
Other flags as above.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-process\-images\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>]
[\-process\-images\-info] [\-process\-images\-force] [\-im <filename>]
[\-jbig2enc <filename>] [\-jbig2dec <filename>]
[\-lossless\-resample[\-dpi] <n> | \-lossless\-to\-jpeg <n>]
[\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg <n>] [\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg\-scale <n>]
[\-lossless\-to\-jpeg2000 <n>] [\-jpeg2000\-to\-jpeg2000 <n>]
[\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg\-dpi <n>] [\-1bpp\-method <method>]
[\-jbig2\-lossy\-threshold <n>] [\-pixel\-threshold <n>]
[\-length\-threshold <n>] [\-percentage\-threshold <n>]
[\-dpi\-threshold <n>] [\-resample\-interpolate] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Re\-process existing images within the PDF, typically to reduce size.
For a full commentary, see cpdfmanual.pdf.
.TP
\f[B]\-process\-images\-info\f[R]
Show the work being done.
.TP
\f[B]\-process\-images\-force\f[R]
Process image even when size would increase.
.TP
\f[B]\-im\f[R] <path>
Supply path to ImageMagick.
.TP
\f[B]\-jbig2enc\f[R] <path>
Supply path to jbig2enc.
.TP
\f[B]\-jbig2dec\f[R] <path>
Supply path to jbig2dec.
.TP
\f[B]\-lossless\-resample\f[R] <n>
Resample lossless images to the given percentage scale.
.TP
\f[B]\-lossless\-resample\-dpi\f[R] <n>
Resample lossless images to a given DPI resolution.
.TP
\f[B]\-lossless\-to\-jpeg\f[R] <n>
Convert lossless images to JPEG at the given quality level.
.TP
\f[B]\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg\f[R] <n>
Reprocess JPEG images to the given quality level.
.TP
\f[B]\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg\-scale\f[R] <n>
Reprocess JPEG images to the given percentage scale.
.TP
\f[B]\-jpeg\-to\-jpeg\-dpi\f[R] <n>
Reprocess JPEG images to the given DPI resolution.
.TP
\f[B]\-lossless\-to\-jpeg2000\f[R] <n>
Convert lossless images to JPEG 2000 at the given quality level.
.TP
\f[B]\-jpeg2000\-to\-jpeg2000\f[R] <n>
Reprocess JPEG 2000 images to the given quality level.
.TP
\f[B]\-1bpp\-method\f[R] <1bppmethod>
Specify method for 1bpp images.
One of \f[B]JBIG2Lossy\f[R], \f[B]JBIG2Lossless\f[R], \f[B]CCITT\f[R],
\f[B]CCITTG4\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\-jbig2\-lossy\-threshold\f[R] <n>
Set the threshold for lossy JBIG2 compression.
.TP
\f[B]\-pixel\-threshold\f[R] <n>
Images below this number of pixels not processed (default 25).
.TP
\f[B]\-length\-threshold\f[R] <n>
Images with less than this number of bytes not processed (default 100).
.TP
\f[B]\-percentage\-threshold\f[R] <n>
Results not below this percentage of original size discarded (default
90).
.TP
\f[B]\-dpi\-threshold\f[R] <n>
Only image above this threshold at all use points processed (default no
dpi threshold).
.TP
\f[B]\-resample\-interpolate\f[R]
Use interpolation when resampling.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-rasterize in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-gs <path>]
[\-rasterize[\-gray | \-1bpp | \-jpeg | \-jpeggray]] [\-rasterize\-res
<n>] [\-rasterize\-jpeg\-quality <n>] [\-rasterize\-no\-antialias |
\-rasterize\-downsample] [\-rasterize\-annots] [\-rasterize\-alpha]
\f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Rasterize each page, replacing the page content with the rasterized
version in the output PDF.
.TP
\f[B]\-gs\f[R] <path>
Supply path to gs.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-gray\f[R]
Use grayscale instead of colour.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-1bpp\f[R]
Use monochrome instead of colour.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-jpeg\f[R]
Use JPEG instead of lossless compression.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-jpeggray\f[R]
Use grayscale JPEG instead of lossless compression.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-res\f[R] <n>
Set the resolution (default 144dpi).
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-jpeg\-quality\f[R] <n>
Set JPEG image quality (0..100).
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-no\-antialias\f[R]
Turn off anti\-aliasing.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-downsample\f[R]
Use better but slower anti\-aliasing.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-annots\f[R]
Rasterize annotations instead of retaining.
.TP
\f[B]\-rasterize\-alpha\f[R]
Produce an alpha channel (lossless only)
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-output\-image in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-gs <path>]
[\-rasterize[\-gray | \-1bpp | \-jpeg | \-jpeggray] [\-rasterize\-res
<n>] [\-rasterize\-jpeg\-quality <n>] [\-rasterize\-no\-antialias |
\-rasterize\-downsample] [\-rasterize\-annots] [\-rasterize\-alpha]
[\-tobox <boxname>] \f[B]\-o <format>\f[R]
.PP
Output rasterized images for each page to the given folder and format
e.g \(lqdir/%%%.png\(rq would create dir/001.png and so on.
Options as above and:
.TP
\f[B]\-tobox\f[R] <boxname>
Specify the box to rasterize (default \f[B]/MediaBox\f[R]).
.SH 14. FONTS
\f[B]cpdf \-list\-fonts[\-json] in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
List the fonts on each page in a file together with their types.
Either in plain text (\f[B]\-list\-fonts\f[R]) or JSON
(\f[B]\-list\-fonts\-json\f[R]) format.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-print\-font\-table <font name>\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R]
[\-print\-font\-table\-page <n>]
.PP
Print a font table for a given font name and page, e.g:
.IP
.EX
cpdf \-print\-font\-table /XYPLPB+NimbusSanL\-Bold \-print\-font\-table\-page 2 cpdfmanual.pdf
67 = U+0043 (C \- LATIN CAPITAL LETTER C) = /C
68 = U+0044 (D \- LATIN CAPITAL LETTER D) = /D
70 = U+0046 (F \- LATIN CAPITAL LETTER F) = /F
71 = U+0047 (G \- LATIN CAPITAL LETTER G) = /G
\&...
.EE
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-copy\-font fromfile.pdf\f[R] \f[B]in.pdf\f[R] [<range>]
\-copy\-font\-page <n> \-copy\-font\-name <name> \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
A low\-level operation to copy a font from one file to another.
.TP
\f[B]\-copy\-font\-page\f[R] <n>
The page from which to copy the font.
.TP
\f[B]\-copy\-font\-name\f[R] <n>
The (PDF) name of the font.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-remove\-fonts in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Remove fonts from a file.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-missing\-fonts in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Report missing fonts \- i.e those which are unembedded.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-embed\-missing\-fonts \-gs <path to gs> in.pdf \-o
out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Use gs to embed missing fonts into a PDF.
Note: putting a PDF file through gs in this manner may not be lossless:
some metadata may not be preserved.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-extract\-font <n>,<pdf font name> in.pdf \-o out.font\f[R]
.PP
Extract a font file from a PDF given a page number, font name pair e.g:
.PP
cpdf \-extract\-font 5,/F50 in.pdf \-o out.ttf
.SH 15. PDF AND JSON
\f[B]cpdf in.pdf \-output\-json\f[R]
[\-output\-json\-parse\-content\-streams]
[\-output\-json\-no\-stream\-data] [\-output\-json\-decompress\-streams]
[\-output\-json\-clean\-strings] [\-utf8] \f[B]\-o out.json\f[R]
.PP
Convert PDF to a JSON format which may be inspected, or edited and
round\-tripped back into PDF.
.TP
\f[B]\-output\-json\-parse\-content\-streams\f[R]
Parse the content streams into JSON too.
.TP
\f[B]\-output\-json\-no\-stream\-data\f[R]
Elide stream data.
This makes a smaller file, but bars round\-tripping.
.TP
\f[B]\-output\-json\-decompress\-streams\f[R]
Keep the streams intact, and decompress them.
.TP
\f[B]\-output\-json\-clean\-strings\f[R]
Deprecated in favour of \f[B]\-utf8\f[R] below.
.TP
\f[B]\-utf8\f[R]
Use UTF8 rather than PDFDocEncoding for strings, to make them more
easily editable.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-j in.json \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Convert a JSON file to a PDF file.
.SH 16. OPTIONAL CONTENT GROUPS
\f[B]cpdf \-ocg\-list in.pdf\f[R]
.PP
List the optional content groups in the PDF, one per line, to standard
output.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-ocg\-rename in.pdf \-ocg\-rename\-from <a> \-ocg\-rename\-to
<b> \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Rename an optional content group given the old and new names.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-ocg\-order\-all in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Ensure that every optional content group appears in the order list.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-ocg\-coalesce\-on\-name in.pdf \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Coalesce optional content groups.
For example, if we merge or stamp two files both with an OCG called
\(lqLayer 1\(rq, we will have two different optional content groups.
This command will merge them into a single optional content group.
.SH 17. CREATING NEW PDFS
\f[B]cpdf \-create\-pdf\f[R] [\-create\-pdf\-pages <n>]
[\-create\-pdf\-papersize <papersize>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Create a new PDF (default: one page, A4 portrait).
.TP
\f[B]\-create\-pdf\-pages\f[R] <n>
Give the number of pages.
.TP
\f[B]\-create\-pdf\-papersize\f[R] <papersize>
Give the paper size, e.g \(lqa3landscape\(rq or \(lq200pt 600pt\(rq
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-typeset <filename>\f[R] [\-create\-pdf\-papersize
<papersize>] [\-font <font>] [\-font\-size <n>] [\-subformat
<subformat>] [\-title <string>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Typeset a text file into a PDF.
.TP
\f[B]\-create\-pdf\-papersize\f[R] <papersize>
Give the paper size.
.TP
\f[B]\-font\f[R] <font>
The font (default Times\-Roman)
.TP
\f[B]\-font\-size\f[R] <n>
The font size (default 12pt)
.TP
\f[B]\-subformat\f[R] <subformat>
Specify PDF/UA\-1 or PDF/UA\-2 to make a conforming file.
.TP
\f[B]\-title\f[R] <string>
Specify a title when using \f[B]\-subformat\f[R] for a PDF/UA file.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-jpeg <filename>\f[R] [\-subformat <subformat>] [\-title
<string>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-png <filename>\f[R] [\-subformat <subformat>] [\-title
<string>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-jpeg2000 <filename>\f[R] [\-subformat <subformat>] [\-title
<string>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Build a PDF from an image file (JPEG, PNG or JPEG2000).
.TP
\f[B]\-subformat\f[R] <subformat>
Specify PDF/UA\-1 or PDF/UA\-2 to make a conforming file.
.TP
\f[B]\-title\f[R] <string>
Specify a title when using \f[B]\-subformat\f[R] for a PDF/UA file.
.PP
\f[B]cpdf\f[R] [\-jbig2\-global <filename>] \f[B]\-jbig2 <filename>\f[R]
[\-jbig2\-global | \-jbig2\-global\-clear] [\-jbig2 <filename>] \&...
[\-subformat <subformat>] [\-title <string>] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
Make a multi\-page PDF from one or more PDF\-appropriate JBIG2 fragments
prepared by the jbig2enc program.
For example, in lossless mode:
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-jbig2 1.jbig2 \-jbig2 2.jbig2 \-jbig2 3.jbig2 \-o
out.pdf\f[R]
.PP
In lossy mode, jbig2globals segments may be specified:
.PP
\f[B]cpdf \-jbig2\-global 0.jbig2globals \-jbig2 1.jbig2 \-jbig2 2.jbig2
\-jbig2 3.jbig2 \-o out.pdf\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-jbig2\-global\f[R] <filename>
Change the jbig2global segment in use.
.TP
\f[B]\-jbig2\-global\-clear\f[R]
Cease use of jbig2global segment, and return to lossless mode.
.TP
\f[B]\-subformat\f[R] <subformat>
Specify PDF/UA\-1 or PDF/UA\-2 to make a conforming file.
.TP
\f[B]\-title\f[R] <string>
Specify a title when using \f[B]\-subformat\f[R] for a PDF/UA file.
.SH 18. DRAWING ON PDFS
\f[B]cpdf in.pdf\f[R] [<range>] [\-draw\-struct\-tree] \f[B]\-draw <draw
operations>\f[R] [\-underneath] \f[B]\-o out.pdf\f[R]
